    <!-- FAQs -->
    <section id="faq" class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

      <div class="space-y-4">
        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I change employers on a Talent Passport?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">Yes, the Talent Passport allows job changes without new visa application, as long as you meet the same criteria (salary threshold, qualification). You must update your préfecture within 2 months of the change. Unlike Salarié visa, no new labor authorization needed.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Is my family automatically covered by Sécurité Sociale?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">Spouse and dependent children are covered as ayants droit (beneficiaries) under your affiliation. They don't pay separate contributions. Apply for their own Carte Vitale after arrival. Non-married partners may need separate enrollment.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">What if I lose my job?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">You can remain in France to job search. Sécurité Sociale coverage continues temporarily via PUMA (universal health protection). If you worked 6+ months, you may qualify for unemployment benefits (chômage). Must find new qualifying employment before visa expires to renew.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Do I need to opt out of employer mutuelle if I have international coverage?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">You can only opt out with specific justifications: spouse's mutuelle covers you, you're a short-term CDD contract, or existing individual contract predating employment. International insurance alone usually isn't valid grounds for opting out of employer mutuelle.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">How do I access my Carte Vitale before it arrives?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">Request an attestation de droits (proof of coverage) from your CPAM (local health insurance office) or via Ameli.fr account. This paper document works at pharmacies and doctors until your physical card arrives. Some providers also accept the Ameli app.</p>
        </div>

        <div class="border border-neutral-200 rounded-lg p-4">
          <h4 class="font-semibold text-neutral-900 mb-2">Can I get permanent residence?</h4>
          <p class="text-neutral-600 text-sm">After 5 years of legal residence, you can apply for carte de résident (10-year permanent residence). Requirements include stable employment, French language proficiency (B1 level), and integration into French society. Some Talent Passport categories have faster pathways.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Final Verdict -->
    <section id="verdict" class="mb-12">
      <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-neutral-900 mb-4">Final Verdict</h2>

      <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-4">
        France's work visa system rewards qualified professionals with access to one of the world's best healthcare systems and strongest worker protections. The Talent Passport has streamlined immigration for skilled workers, avoiding the lengthy labor market tests that plague standard work visas elsewhere in Europe.
      </p>

      <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-4">
        The Sécurité Sociale system means you rarely think about health insurance once enrolled. Pre-existing conditions are covered without question. The mandatory employer mutuelle fills most gaps. For the 4-8 week transition period, basic travel or international insurance provides adequate bridge coverage.
      </p>

      <p class="text-neutral-700 mb-4">
        The trade-offs are real: high taxes reduce take-home pay significantly, bureaucracy can be frustrating, and French language proficiency is essential for daily life outside of international company bubbles. But for those who embrace la vie française, the quality of life, work-life balance, and social protections are hard to match.
      </p>

      <div class="bg-primary-50 border border-primary-200 rounded-lg p-6 mt-6">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-primary-900 mb-2">Bottom Line</h3>
        <p class="text-primary-800">The France work visa is excellent for skilled professionals who value work-life balance, job security, and comprehensive healthcare over maximizing income. The Talent Passport makes immigration straightforward for qualified workers. Plan for a short transition period with bridge insurance, then enjoy one of the world's best public healthcare systems.</p>
      </div>
    </section>

